So far so good. That is pretty

00:09:44.000 --> 00:09:50.000
simple. Now let's look at planes.
For planes we use something called

00:09:50.000 --> 00:09:56.000
the Miller indices for describing
planes. And they are named after

00:09:56.000 --> 00:10:02.000
the British mineralogist William
Hallowes Miller who,

00:10:02.000 --> 00:10:08.000
back in the 1830s, gave us this
means of describing a plane.

00:10:08.000 --> 00:10:12.000
And I think, rather than writing it
down, we will just follow along here

00:10:12.000 --> 00:10:16.000
because you have the notes in front
of you. You know from your math

00:10:16.000 --> 00:10:20.000
that the equation of a plane is x
over a plus y over b plus z over c

00:10:20.000 --> 00:10:24.000
equals one, **x/a + y/b + z/c = 1**
and a, b and c are the intercepts

00:10:24.000 --> 00:10:28.000
with the x, y and z axes
respectively. What Miller did is he

00:10:28.000 --> 00:10:32.000
said let's let h be one over a,
k be one over b and l equals one

00:10:32.000 --> 00:10:56.270
over c.
So this becomes the equation of the

00:10:56.270 --> 00:11:00.810
plane, hx plus ky plus lz equals one.
**hx + ky + lz = 1** And now what

00:11:00.810 --> 00:11:05.360
you do is take the h,
k and l and enclose those in

00:11:05.360 --> 00:11:09.900
parentheses. In other words,
he is taking the plane index to be

00:11:09.900 --> 00:11:14.450
the reciprocals of the intercepts
with the three axes.

00:11:14.450 --> 00:11:33.366
And you will see why in a second.
Why do it that way?

00:10:59.000 --> 00:11:03.000
Because every once in a while
something like this happens.

00:11:03.000 --> 00:11:07.000
Here is a simple one just to get
our feet wet. Here a,

00:11:07.000 --> 00:11:11.000
b and c are the unit vectors,
so this is the x-axis in the same

00:11:11.000 --> 00:11:15.000
convention I have chosen.
X is coming out of the plane of the

00:11:15.000 --> 00:11:19.000
slide, y is moving to the right and
z is moving up.

00:11:19.000 --> 00:11:23.000
Here is a plane that is shaded in.
And what do you see? It cuts the

00:11:23.000 --> 00:11:27.000
x-axis at x equals plus one-half,
it cuts the y-axis at y equals plus

00:11:27.000 --> 00:11:31.000
one, and it never cuts the z-axis.
It is parallel to the z-axis.

00:11:31.000 --> 00:11:35.000
Mathematically,
we would say the z-intercept is

00:11:35.000 --> 00:11:39.000
infinity. And who wants to have
infinity? Now you see the wisdom of

00:11:39.000 --> 00:11:43.000
Miller. Miller said let's describe
this in terms of the reciprocals.

00:11:43.000 --> 00:11:47.000
What is the reciprocal of one-half?
It is two. What is the reciprocal

00:11:47.000 --> 00:11:51.000
of one? It is one.
And what is the reciprocal of

00:11:51.000 --> 00:11:55.000
infinity? Zero.
We can describe this plane as the

00:11:55.000 --> 00:12:18.940
two, one, zero plane.
Whenever you see a zero,

00:12:18.940 --> 00:12:22.820
whatever place the zero lies that
means that plane is parallel to that

00:12:22.820 --> 00:12:26.700
axis, so right away I can say that
is a plane that is parallel to the

00:12:26.700 --> 00:12:30.580
z-axis. It does not cross the
z-axis. So there it is.

00:12:30.580 --> 00:12:34.460
There is the formula. You take the
reciprocal of the intercepts,

00:12:34.460 --> 00:12:38.350
put them side-by-side, no commas,
and this is why we save the

00:12:38.350 --> 00:12:42.230
parentheses. That is why we don't
put our position in parentheses

00:12:42.230 --> 00:12:46.110
because we are saving parentheses
for the plane.

