00:24:25.920 --> 00:24:30.530
manifestation of what you have seen
as the ground state energy in the

00:24:30.530 --> 00:24:35.150
Bohr model goes as the square of the
atomic number.

00:24:35.150 --> 00:24:39.760
Everything is making sense,
but what I draw your attention to is,

00:24:39.760 --> 00:24:44.380
look, this is the innermost held
electron of nitrogen.

00:24:44.380 --> 00:25:04.226
It is 668 electron volts and I have
12,400. This has enormous power.

00:24:29.000 --> 00:24:55.190
This has the power to ionize inner
shell electrons.

00:24:55.190 --> 00:25:01.390
This is like a bowling alley.
All the pins are going flying here.

00:25:01.390 --> 00:25:07.590
This is incredible energy. What
are the underlying principles here?

00:25:07.590 --> 00:25:13.790
Well, I think we have to start with
a history lesson.

00:25:13.790 --> 00:25:29.913
We will go back to November 8,
1895.

00:25:00.000 --> 00:25:29.140
It was a dark and stormy night,
really. It was a dark and stormy

00:25:29.140 --> 00:25:38.280
night on November 8,
1895 in WŸrzburg, Bavaria,

00:25:38.280 --> 00:25:47.420
which is now part of Germany.
There was a physics professor there

00:25:47.420 --> 00:25:54.130
by the name of Wilhelm Roentgen.
And he was doing research,

00:25:54.130 --> 00:25:58.390
as many people were at that time,
on gas discharge tubes. We have

00:25:58.390 --> 00:26:02.660
seen gas discharge tubes a number of
times in 3.091,

00:26:02.660 --> 00:26:06.930
and Roentgen was part of that army
of researchers.

00:26:06.930 --> 00:26:11.190
And what Roentgen's specialty was,
he was pursuing gas discharge

00:26:11.190 --> 00:26:15.460
spectral analysis under reduced
pressure. He was pumping down with

00:26:15.460 --> 00:26:19.730
a vacuum pump to get the gas
pressure very,

00:26:19.730 --> 00:26:37.926
very low, and very,
very high voltage.

00:26:04.000 --> 00:26:28.720
That is what his take was.
He wanted to look at high voltage

00:26:28.720 --> 00:26:33.450
and very, very low pressure.
And let's take a look at what his

00:26:33.450 --> 00:26:38.180
apparatus looked like.
Well, we will start with the tube.

00:26:38.180 --> 00:26:42.900
As you have seen many times, we
will put the cathode to the left and

00:26:42.900 --> 00:26:47.630
we will put the anode to the right.
And he had the laboratory on the

00:26:47.630 --> 00:27:06.093
second floor.
His apartment was on the first floor.

00:26:32.500 --> 00:26:37.500
And down in the basement he had a
bunch of batteries.

00:26:37.500 --> 00:26:42.500
Chromic acid in open beakers down
in the basement.

00:26:42.500 --> 00:26:47.500
Let's indicate that with the
classical symbol.

00:26:47.500 --> 00:26:52.500
And this altogether put out about
20 volts. And he was a professor of

00:26:52.500 --> 00:26:57.500
physics who understood some
electrical engineering. He

00:26:57.500 --> 00:27:03.000
had a choke coil here.
The choke coil would take the

00:27:03.000 --> 00:27:09.000
current, store up,
and eight times a second it would

00:27:09.000 --> 00:27:15.000
discharge. And it would discharge
at 35,000 volts.

00:27:15.000 --> 00:27:21.000
He could take 20 volts and up it to
35,000 by the use of this choke coil.

00:27:21.000 --> 00:27:27.000
Eight times a second he had 35,
00 volts coming off the cathode here.

00:27:27.000 --> 00:27:52.300
You have bam, bam, bam.
But speed that up about eight times.

00:27:52.300 --> 00:27:56.920
That is what is going on. And so
with 35,000 volts he launches

00:27:56.920 --> 00:28:01.530
electrons off the cathode,
and they go zooming across what is

00:28:01.530 --> 00:28:06.150
very, very low pressure gas and
crash into the anode.

00:28:06.150 --> 00:28:10.760
In the meantime, to keep this thing
dynamically at low pressure,

00:28:10.760 --> 00:28:15.380
this goes to a vacuum pump to keep
this thing pumped down as low as he

00:28:15.380 --> 00:28:35.026
can. And he was measuring what was
going on inside this gas tube.

00:28:00.000 --> 00:28:25.380
And so he had a detector.
His detector was over here off to

00:28:25.380 --> 00:28:30.760
the side. The detector consisted of
either a piece of cloth or a paper

00:28:30.760 --> 00:28:36.150
towel which had been painted with a
chemical that would glow when it was

00:28:36.150 --> 00:28:41.530
struck by something.
What would the something be?

00:28:41.530 --> 00:28:46.920
The something would be electrons or
photons that have an energy high

00:28:46.920 --> 00:28:52.300
enough to cause excitation of
something in the paint and then

00:28:52.300 --> 00:28:58.220
reemission in the visible.
It doesn't do any good to excite

00:28:58.220 --> 00:29:04.660
electrons in the detector to have
them reemit outside the visible.

00:29:04.660 --> 00:29:11.110
That is what is going on. This was
paper or cloth,

00:29:11.110 --> 00:29:17.550
and it was painted with an aqueous
solution of barium plantinocyanide

00:29:17.550 --> 00:29:33.500
which glows green when
it is excited.

00:29:04.000 --> 00:29:29.190
And this is called a scintillation
screen. It comes from the Latin

00:29:29.190 --> 00:29:34.390
word for spark.
Scintilla means spark in Latin.

00:29:34.390 --> 00:29:39.590
When the screen is struck by some
form of energy it will glow.

00:29:39.590 --> 00:29:44.790
And so he had dinner. He was up on
the second floor cranking away after

00:29:44.790 --> 00:30:03.313
dinner. It was dark and raining.
He had the windows open.

00:29:30.000 --> 00:29:53.730
And a streetlight was coming in.
Oh, by the way, Roentgen suffered

00:29:53.730 --> 00:29:57.460
from Daltonism.
He was red-green colored blind.

00:29:57.460 --> 00:30:01.190
And this was a green screen. And
with 35,000 volts,

00:30:01.190 --> 00:30:04.930
even at reduced pressure,
given the capacity of those days for

00:30:04.930 --> 00:30:08.660
vacuum pumps, he still had a lot of
glow from the tube.

00:30:08.660 --> 00:30:12.390
The tube is glowing,
he has a streetlight in the

00:30:12.390 --> 00:30:16.130
background, so he decides to close
the drapes and take out

00:30:16.130 --> 00:30:34.793
the streetlight.
And then, furthermore,

00:30:00.000 --> 00:30:04.000
he decides to darken the room so he
puts a cardboard box over the tube.

00:30:04.000 --> 00:30:08.000
Now the tube is enclosed in a
cardboard box so it is not glowing

00:30:08.000 --> 00:30:12.000
visibly to him.
It is glowing inside the box.

00:30:12.000 --> 00:30:16.000
And he continues to see
scintillation,

00:30:16.000 --> 00:30:20.000
continues to see things glowing.
He says that is something

00:30:20.000 --> 00:30:24.000
interesting. The other thing that
happened which was kind of

00:30:24.000 --> 00:30:28.000
interesting, his graduate student
who had prepared some

00:30:28.000 --> 00:30:52.410
of the apparatus --
I guess he was practicing painting

00:30:52.410 --> 00:30:57.240
the scintillation screen.
What the student had done was to

00:30:57.240 --> 00:31:02.080
paint the letter A on a paper towel,
and he left the paper towel on the

00:31:02.080 --> 00:31:06.910
lab bench. Now,
Röntgen has the tube enclosed in

00:31:06.910 --> 00:31:11.740
cardboard, this thing is glowing and
he looks down and sees the letter A

00:31:11.740 --> 00:31:16.580
and the letter A is glowing.
He is going, wait a minute, this is

00:31:16.580 --> 00:31:21.210
crazy.
He takes a piece of black paper and

00:31:21.210 --> 00:31:25.640
puts it here in between the tube and
the screen, and the screen continues

00:31:25.640 --> 00:31:30.070
to glow. He had a deck of playing
cards in his lab.

00:31:30.070 --> 00:31:34.490
Don't laugh. That is how Mendeleev
discovered periodicity.

00:31:34.490 --> 00:31:38.920
He takes a playing card and puts it
in front and the tube continues to

00:31:38.920 --> 00:31:43.350
glow. And then he takes a book and
puts it in between and the tube

00:31:43.350 --> 00:31:47.780
continues to glow.
He is going wait a minute.

00:31:47.780 --> 00:31:52.410
Then he grabs a piece of lead foil.
He puts the lead foil in here.

00:31:52.410 --> 00:31:57.240
And what happens is that where the
lead foil is the screen is not

00:31:57.240 --> 00:32:02.080
glowing, but then he sees the
outline of the bones of his hand on

00:32:02.080 --> 00:32:06.910
the lead holding the lead foil.
All of this stuff is going on, and

00:32:06.910 --> 00:32:11.740
he just goes to town.
He says, you know what,

00:32:11.740 --> 00:32:16.580
this cannot be electrons because
electrons cannot live in air.

00:32:16.580 --> 00:32:21.280
They will be stopped by air.
And he knew about radio waves from

00:32:21.280 --> 00:32:25.850
Hertz and said could this be some
form of mysterious radiation that is

00:32:25.850 --> 00:32:30.420
capable, and he was really afraid to
say this, of penetrating matter?

00:32:30.420 --> 00:32:34.990
It is 1895. Are you going to come
out publicly and say I have a form

00:32:34.990 --> 00:32:39.570
of radiation that can penetrate
matter? He gets a magnet out.

00:32:39.570 --> 00:32:44.140
He moves a magnet and it doesn't
change, so this stuff is not

00:32:44.140 --> 00:32:48.710
sensitive to magnetic field.
But, if he puts a magnet here,

00:32:48.710 --> 00:32:53.380
of course he gets changes.
He cannot see this stuff.

00:32:53.380 --> 00:32:58.150
He can only see evidence of it.
It is mysterious. He calls it x,

00:32:58.150 --> 00:33:02.920
the unknown quantity. It is x
radiation. This is November 8,

00:33:02.920 --> 00:33:07.690
1895. And, to show you what a great
scientist he was,

00:33:07.690 --> 00:33:12.460
rather than rushing to publication,
he spends all of November and

00:33:12.460 --> 00:33:17.230
December repeating the experiment
and trying it in different ways

00:33:17.230 --> 00:33:35.460
until he is convinced that
the effect is real.

00:33:02.000 --> 00:33:26.610
And then around Christmas time of
1895 he sends off a manuscript.

00:33:26.610 --> 00:33:31.220
And it is published in the first
week of January of 1896 and takes

00:33:31.220 --> 00:33:35.840
the world by storm.
He is announcing that there is a

00:33:35.840 --> 00:33:40.460
form of radiation that can penetrate
matter. And, furthermore,

00:33:40.460 --> 00:33:45.070
he has an x-ray of a human hand.
This is the 1890s and people are

00:33:45.070 --> 00:33:49.690
very prude, very private,
and he has a form of radiation that

00:33:49.690 --> 00:33:54.450
can look inside the human body.
This is really shocking stuff.

00:33:54.450 --> 00:33:59.360
Already on January 16, 1896 there
is an article in The New York Times

00:33:59.360 --> 00:34:04.270
about this stuff,
a mysterious form of radiation.

00:34:04.270 --> 00:34:09.170
By the way, when he was doing these
experiments how was he recording his

00:34:09.170 --> 00:34:14.080
results? He was recording his
results on photographic film,

00:34:14.080 --> 00:34:31.626
and his photographic film was
fogging.

00:33:59.000 --> 00:34:23.280
He had his photographic film stored
in a cabinet on the other side of

00:34:23.280 --> 00:34:27.560
the lab, and half of the time he
would take the photographic film out

00:34:27.560 --> 00:34:31.850
and it was fogged.
He said whatever this stuff is,

00:34:31.850 --> 00:34:36.140
it is penetrating everything. It is
penetrating the doors of his file

00:34:36.140 --> 00:34:40.420
cabinet. They weren't steel cased.
They were probably wooden file

00:34:40.420 --> 00:34:44.710
cabinets. So,
widespread adoption,

00:34:44.710 --> 00:35:03.686
some of it silly. What are some of
the silly ones?

00:34:29.000 --> 00:34:53.130
In London there was a manufacturer
who announced,

00:34:53.130 --> 00:34:57.260
remember this is prudish Victorian
England, that he could sell you

00:34:57.260 --> 00:35:01.390
x-ray proof ladies underwear.
In France, there was no such thing.

00:35:01.390 --> 00:35:05.530
The French don't care about such
matters. Remember,

00:35:05.530 --> 00:35:09.660
the French Daguerre had invented
halide photography.

00:35:09.660 --> 00:35:13.790
So someone in France offered to
x-ray the human soul.

00:35:13.790 --> 00:35:17.930
This is very good. I am ashamed to
say what happened in

00:35:17.930 --> 00:35:22.800
the United States.
The New York City College of

00:35:22.800 --> 00:35:28.400
Physicians and Surgeons announced
that they would use x-rays to

00:35:28.400 --> 00:35:47.333
project anatomical diagrams from
textbooks onto the brains of medical

00:35:14.000 --> 00:35:39.600
students, thereby creating,
and I quote, an enduring impression.

00:35:39.600 --> 00:35:45.190
In Iowa, somebody offered to x-ray
copper pennies and thereby turn them

00:35:45.190 --> 00:35:49.770
into gold. That is what happened.
But, seriously,

00:35:49.770 --> 00:35:53.330
what really did happen very quickly
was the use of x-rays as a

00:35:53.330 --> 00:35:56.880
diagnostic tool.
Already in February of 1896 there

00:35:56.880 --> 00:36:00.440
was a Scottish physician who used
x-rays. It is simple.

00:36:00.440 --> 00:36:03.990
You could do this in a high school.
I mean what is it? It is just a

00:36:03.990 --> 00:36:07.550
gas discharge tube,
a pair of electrodes with a feed

00:36:07.550 --> 00:36:11.100
through, and he has 35,
00 volts, I mean that is the kind of

00:36:11.100 --> 00:36:14.660
stuff that comes off the chassis of
your television set.

00:36:14.660 --> 00:36:18.220
This is trivial stuff.
People were putting these things

00:36:18.220 --> 00:36:21.870
everywhere.
They were sitting in offices in open

00:36:21.870 --> 00:36:25.620
view. Nobody knew.
This physician had a seamstress

00:36:25.620 --> 00:36:29.370
come to him. She was involved in an
industrial accident in a mill.

00:36:29.370 --> 00:36:33.120
A needle broke off in her hand.
Now, how would you find the needle

00:36:33.120 --> 00:36:36.870
in a hand? You cannot.
X-ray, they identified the location

00:36:36.870 --> 00:36:40.620
of the needle,
performed the surgery and boom.

00:36:40.620 --> 00:36:44.370
For dental applications it was
immediately adopted.

00:36:44.370 --> 00:36:48.120
They were already using it in 1899
as a form of treatment for cancer.

00:36:48.120 --> 00:36:52.300
Very interesting.
It took over. What is the relative

00:36:52.300 --> 00:36:56.920
physics? What is going on here?
Where do we have to go? I say we

00:36:56.920 --> 00:37:01.530
have to look at the anode because
that is where the electrons are

00:37:01.530 --> 00:37:06.150
crashing into.
That is the site of the collision.

00:37:06.150 --> 00:37:10.760
Something is happening at that
anode. Let's look inside the anode.

00:37:10.760 --> 00:37:15.380
Suppose it is copper, what could we
say about it? This is where the

00:37:15.380 --> 00:37:34.026
electron collision is.
That is the maximum impact.

00:37:00.000 --> 00:37:25.270
Let's just see what might be going
on. I want to show you the power of

00:37:25.270 --> 00:37:30.540
estimation. I have shown you that
with nitrogen it is 668 electron

00:37:30.540 --> 00:37:35.810
volts to get to the inner shell
electrons. What about in the case

00:37:35.810 --> 00:37:41.080
of the anode? What is going on
there? Well, I can say what is the

00:37:41.080 --> 00:37:46.360
energy of the 1s electron in copper
28 plus? That is a one

00:37:46.360 --> 00:37:51.270
electron system.
And you know that in real copper

00:37:51.270 --> 00:37:55.810
with all of its electrons this value
is going to be an over-estimate

00:37:55.810 --> 00:38:00.360
because the presence of all the
other electrons is going to sap some

00:38:00.360 --> 00:38:04.900
of the protonic Coulombic force.
This will be an upper bound of what

00:38:04.900 --> 00:38:09.450
that energy could be.
And we know that is simply equal to

00:38:09.450 --> 00:38:28.100
the energy of the 1s in hydrogen
times z squared.

00:37:54.000 --> 00:37:59.000
If I take 13.6 electron volts times
29 squared, I get 11.

00:37:59.000 --> 00:38:04.000
thousand electron volts,
which is still less than the 35

00:38:04.000 --> 00:38:09.000
thousand electron volts that
Roentgen had. Roentgen is running a

00:38:09.000 --> 00:38:14.000
huge bowling alley here.
He is able to knock out 1s

00:38:14.000 --> 00:38:19.000
electrons from copper.
And what happens when you knock out

00:38:19.000 --> 00:38:24.000
inner shell electrons?
What is the next thing that happens?

00:38:24.000 --> 00:38:29.000
Let's look at an energy
level diagram.

00:38:29.000 --> 00:38:53.130
Let's suppose that this is the anode.
This is the anode in the gas tube.

00:38:53.130 --> 00:38:57.260
This is an energy level diagram.
This is going to be n equals

00:38:57.260 --> 00:39:01.390
infinity. And we will just do a few
of them. This is n equals four,

00:39:01.390 --> 00:39:05.530
n equals three, n equals two and n
equals one. Not to scale.

00:39:05.530 --> 00:39:09.660
I am trying to show that they are a
little bit farther apart as you go

00:39:09.660 --> 00:39:13.790
lower and lower.
And so this is ground state energy

00:39:13.790 --> 00:39:17.930
E1, this is n equals two shell,
n equals three shell, n equals four

00:39:17.930 --> 00:39:22.300
shell.
And out here it is zero.

00:39:22.300 --> 00:39:26.920
And so what do I have? I have some
incident electron that comes zooming

00:39:26.920 --> 00:39:31.530
in here. This is incident.
This is the one that has been

00:39:31.530 --> 00:39:36.150
accelerated. The energy of this
electron is all kinetic.

00:39:36.150 --> 00:39:40.760
And that is equal to product of the
charge on the electron which is

00:39:40.760 --> 00:39:45.380
elemental e times a plate voltage
which is 35 thousand volts.

00:39:45.380 --> 00:40:04.626
That is how I get 35 thousand
electron volts as the energy.

00:39:30.000 --> 00:39:54.610
And we have just shown that it has
enough energy that it can even knock

00:39:54.610 --> 00:39:59.220
out an inner shell electron.
It can even dislodge an inner shell

00:39:59.220 --> 00:40:03.840
electron. Let's see what would
happen if that were the case.

00:40:03.840 --> 00:40:08.460
It dislodges an inner shell
electron. What is the next thing?

00:40:08.460 --> 00:40:13.070
I have a vacancy down here. What
will happen? One electron will fall

00:40:13.070 --> 00:40:17.690
from n equals two to n equals one.
And when it does so it gives off

00:40:17.690 --> 00:40:31.380
radiation.

00:40:05.000 --> 00:40:28.570
Well, if it falls from n equals two
to n equals one,

00:40:28.570 --> 00:40:32.140
there is a slim chance it might even
fall from n equals three to n equals

00:40:32.140 --> 00:40:35.710
one or maybe even n equals four to n
equals one. Well,

00:40:35.710 --> 00:40:39.280
heck, if it can go from two to one,
there is a vacancy in two. I might

00:40:39.280 --> 00:40:42.850
get three to two,
I might get four to two,

00:40:42.850 --> 00:40:46.420
and you get the picture. You get a
whole cascade here.

00:40:46.420 --> 00:41:06.306
Each one of these gives off photons,
photon emission.

00:40:30.000 --> 00:40:56.900
You have expulsion of k shell all of
the electrons,

00:40:56.900 --> 00:41:03.810
but you can go all the way down to
the k shell electrons and then

00:41:03.810 --> 00:41:10.720
cascade and accompanied by
photoemission.

00:41:10.720 --> 00:41:17.630
The difference is that instead of
being in the visible or the infrared,

00:41:17.630 --> 00:41:24.540
these energy levels are so,
so tightly bound that this is in the

00:41:24.540 --> 00:41:42.113
x region of the spectrum.
And we have labels for these

00:41:10.500 --> 00:41:15.500
different photons.
And, first of all,

00:41:15.500 --> 00:41:20.500
the spectroscopists don't like the
numbers. This is the chemist

00:41:20.500 --> 00:41:25.500
notation, n equals one,
n equals two, n equals three,

00:41:25.500 --> 00:41:30.500
n equals four. The spectroscopists
call the ground state k shell,

00:41:30.500 --> 00:41:56.220
this is m shell, this is n shell.
I left out a letter in the alphabet.

00:41:56.220 --> 00:42:02.660
K, l shell, m shell, n shell. We
can label this as a photon that came

00:42:02.660 --> 00:42:09.110
from a cascade down to the k shell.
And to distinguish this k shell

00:42:09.110 --> 00:42:15.550
electron from the k shell electron
involving a transition from n equals

00:42:15.550 --> 00:42:32.700
three down to n equals one,
we have a second indicator.

00:42:02.000 --> 00:42:30.750
And that is the subscript alpha.
This means the cascade down to k

00:42:30.750 --> 00:42:46.533
shell and the alpha represents how
far the electron traveled from one

00:42:19.500 --> 00:42:48.250
shell away. That means from n
equals two to n equals one,

00:42:48.250 --> 00:43:02.766
this is a k beta photon, this is a k
gamma photon.

00:42:37.000 --> 00:43:00.830
This is like a Lyman series.
This is like a Balmer series

00:43:00.830 --> 00:43:04.660
because it always ends at n equals
two. N equals three to n equals two

00:43:04.660 --> 00:43:08.490
gives us a photon,
and that photon is going to be

00:43:08.490 --> 00:43:12.330
called L alpha.
N equals four to n equals two will

00:43:12.330 --> 00:43:16.160
give us a photon,
and that is going to be called L

00:43:16.160 --> 00:43:34.986
beta. I am going to get
a whole spectrum.

00:43:00.000 --> 00:43:24.830
Let's take a look at what that
spectrum might look like.

00:43:24.830 --> 00:43:29.660
I could calculate any one of these.
I could say lambda of copper k

00:43:29.660 --> 00:43:34.490
alpha would equal what?
It is the same as you have seen

00:43:34.490 --> 00:43:39.330
before, hc over what?
The energy of n equals two shell to

00:43:39.330 --> 00:43:44.160
energy of n equals one shell.
**lambda Cu K alpha = hc/(E2-E1)

00:43:44.160 --> 00:44:01.653
What can we do? We
can measure this.

00:43:29.000 --> 00:43:53.610
We know h and c.
We can calculate what those energy

00:43:53.610 --> 00:43:58.220
levels are. Let's plot this out.
I could make a plot of wavelength

00:43:58.220 --> 00:44:02.840
intensity and I will get an entire
spectrum of lines.

00:44:02.840 --> 00:44:07.460
This is high wavelength so that
means energy is increasing from

00:44:07.460 --> 00:44:12.070
right to left.
The highest energy is over here.

00:44:12.070 --> 00:44:16.690
What's the highest energy up there?
The highest energy looks like n

00:44:16.690 --> 00:44:21.900
equals four down to n equals one.
And that is going to be over here.

00:44:21.900 --> 00:44:27.700
This could be k gamma, then k beta,
k alpha. And then the L lines are

00:44:27.700 --> 00:44:33.490
three to two, four to two,
so they are over here. This is L

00:44:33.490 --> 00:44:39.290
alpha, L beta and so on.
And these different wavelengths are

00:44:39.290 --> 00:44:45.090
associated with different energies.
And these different energies are

00:44:45.090 --> 00:44:50.900
associated with what?
They are associated with the binding

00:44:50.900 --> 00:44:56.720
inside the atom,
inside the target.

00:44:56.720 --> 00:45:02.540
Every target has its own number of
protons, its own number of electrons,

00:45:02.540 --> 00:45:08.360
so this set of lines is
characteristic of the target.

00:45:08.360 --> 00:45:14.180
And I had to do a whole year of
x-ray crystallography as a junior

00:45:14.180 --> 00:45:32.560
back at the University of Toronto.
We used copper as the target.

00:45:00.000 --> 00:45:25.070
And I will know on my deathbed that
the wavelength of copper k alpha is

00:45:25.070 --> 00:45:30.150
1.5418 angstroms.
If I walk into the room and see 1.

00:45:30.150 --> 00:45:35.220
418 angstroms, that is copper. It
comes from copper.

00:45:35.220 --> 00:45:40.300
And any other element is going to
give me a different set of lines.

00:45:40.300 --> 00:45:45.380
What I am learning here is I have a
way of identifying elements.

00:45:45.380 --> 00:45:50.460
This is now turning into something
that could be a technique

00:45:50.460 --> 00:45:55.750
of chemical analysis.
And we will return next day to see

00:45:55.750 --> 00:46:01.250
what else we can do with it.
For the last five minutes, I am

00:46:01.250 --> 00:46:06.750
going to show you a little bit more
about Roentgen and his discovery.

00:46:06.750 --> 00:46:12.250
But I wanted to just draw attention
to our winner from Friday who was

00:46:12.250 --> 00:46:17.750
unable to attend the lecture.
And so I want to ask Nivair Gabriel

00:46:17.750 --> 00:46:23.250
to stand and accept her
acknowledgment for the fine job she

00:46:23.250 --> 00:46:27.800
did on the Actinides thing.
And she is wearing her scarf.

00:46:27.800 --> 00:46:31.400
Why don't you come down and people
can see you wearing the really super

00:46:31.400 --> 00:46:50.866
hot American Chemical Society
scarf. [APPLAUSE]

00:46:15.000 --> 00:46:46.660
Now, here is the dark and stormy

00:46:46.660 --> 00:47:05.986
night the following morning.
It is sunny.

00:46:30.000 --> 00:46:55.810
This is Roentgen's laboratory on the
second floor of his flat in WŸrzburg.

00:46:55.810 --> 00:47:01.630
It is a museum today.
And you can see the tubes and the

00:47:01.630 --> 00:47:07.450
lead wires going down to the
basement and so on.

00:47:07.450 --> 00:47:13.270
Hold it. I don't want a lot of
noise. This is the first radiograph

00:47:13.270 --> 00:47:19.090
ever. This is Roentgen's wife
Bertha. He noticed that there was a

00:47:19.090 --> 00:47:24.150
shadow with the lead.
Roentgen was smart.

00:47:24.150 --> 00:47:28.460
He had to share the glory so he
said, honey, would you mind coming

00:47:28.460 --> 00:47:32.760
upstairs, I would like to take your
picture. And so Bertha put her hand

00:47:32.760 --> 00:47:37.070
in the path of the x-ray,
and for 15 full minutes waited while

00:47:37.070 --> 00:47:41.380
those x-rays went through.
You can see the ring on her finger

00:47:41.380 --> 00:47:45.690
and so on. She endured in that 15
minutes greater than a lifetime dose

00:47:45.690 --> 00:48:06.046
of what we would consider safe today.
People just did not know. Anyway.

00:47:30.000 --> 00:47:54.920
This gave birth to medical
radiography. And I would,

00:47:54.920 --> 00:47:59.840
just out of curiosity, like to know
if there is anybody in this room who

00:47:59.840 --> 00:48:04.760
has never had a medical or dental
x-ray. I see very few.

00:48:04.760 --> 00:48:09.690
I see a few hands. To you I say
congratulations and I hope you keep

00:48:09.690 --> 00:48:14.610
up the good work.
Here is the second thing.

00:48:14.610 --> 00:48:19.530
We have radiography that came out
of Roentgen's discovery.

00:48:19.530 --> 00:48:23.860
Roentgen had a torsion balance.
Like the Justice,

00:48:23.860 --> 00:48:27.590
she has the two scales.
On one scale you put the unknown

00:48:27.590 --> 00:48:31.330
and the other scale you put the
calibrated mass.

00:48:31.330 --> 00:48:35.060
He had a set of brass weights here
in a wooden box,

00:48:35.060 --> 00:48:38.790
and he closed the wooden box and
irradiated the box with the x-rays

00:48:38.790 --> 00:48:42.530
and took this photograph.
And what do you see? You see that

00:48:42.530 --> 00:48:46.260
different materials have different
electron densities and,

00:48:46.260 --> 00:49:06.453
therefore, the wood is transparent,
more or less, to x-rays.

00:48:30.000 --> 00:48:55.090
Whereas, the brass is less so.
You have a differentiation. The

00:48:55.090 --> 00:49:00.180
way we see things is by
differentiation.

00:49:00.180 --> 00:49:05.270
Here you have a differentiation.
He could identify what was in the

00:49:05.270 --> 00:49:10.360
box when the box was closed.
That gives rise to security

00:49:10.360 --> 00:49:15.450
technology. Every time you go to
the airport you are subjected to

00:49:15.450 --> 00:49:20.640
this, and it started with Roentgen.
Roentgen also had a gun.

00:49:20.640 --> 00:49:25.920
It was a musket. He wasn't holding
up convenience stores.

00:49:25.920 --> 00:49:31.210
What are you laughing at?
He had a gun. He went hunting.

00:49:31.210 --> 00:49:36.490
He took an x-radiograph of his gun.
And this is used today. It gives

00:49:36.490 --> 00:49:41.780
birth to the technology of failure
analysis. In fact,

00:49:41.780 --> 00:49:47.070
there are certain types of weld,
typically involving very dangerous

00:49:47.070 --> 00:49:52.350
circumstances such as pressure
vessels that are going to contain

00:49:52.350 --> 00:49:57.800
steam at very, very high pressures.
The code is that every inch of the

00:49:57.800 --> 00:50:03.400
welded seam must be inspected by
x-radiation in order to find what?

00:50:03.400 --> 00:50:22.466
Internal cracks. Because, if there
is a crack, there is a difference in

00:49:49.000 --> 00:50:14.600
electron density.
And so you will see contrast in the

00:50:14.600 --> 00:50:20.190
x-ray photograph.
From that experiment come three

00:50:20.190 --> 00:50:25.150
technologies.
And for his work,

00:50:25.150 --> 00:50:29.460
Roentgen was the recipient of the
very first Nobel prize in physics.

00:50:29.460 --> 00:50:33.760
It was awarded in 1901. He was the
unanimous choice of the world

00:50:33.760 --> 00:50:38.070
physics community for what he had
done. And you are going to see next

00:50:38.070 --> 00:50:42.380
day more that the discovery of
x-rays enabled.

00:50:42.380 --> 00:50:46.690
But one last thing,
what a fine human being he was.

00:50:46.690 --> 00:51:04.913
You know what he did with his
winnings?

00:50:31.000 --> 00:50:35.500
He donated them to the University of
WŸrzburg to be made an endowment for

00:50:35.500 --> 00:50:40.000
student scholarships.
And, to this day, physics students

00:50:40.000 --> 00:50:44.500
at the University of WŸrzburg are
recipients of scholarships that were

00:50:44.500 --> 00:50:49.000
endowed by Roentgen with his Nobel
prize winnings in 1901.

00:50:49.000 --> 00:50:50.866
I will see you on Wednesday.

